t women" redress efforts, state-sponsored apologies and amnesties, Asian American involvement in redress cases, the ongoing effects of the U.S. occupation of Japan and Okinawa, Japanese atrocities in China, and battles over WWII memories-Yoneyama helps illuminate how redress culture across Asia and the Pacific has the potential to bring powerful new and challenging perspectives on American exceptionalism, militarized security, justice, sovereignty, forgiveness, and decolonization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aCold War. 0aDecolonization. 0aNationalism and feminism. 0aReparations for historical injustices - Japan. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszJapan. 0aTransnationalism. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocitieszJapan. 4aAAAS Book Award Winners. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374114zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822374114.jpg  a978-3-11-070808-0  DUK Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles